07210nam a22009135i 9780691234168DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20211996nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912341687 a10.1515/97806912341682doi  a(DE-B1597)589779  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aJC423b.D43979 1996eb 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a321.822200aDemocracy and Difference :bContesting the Boundaries of the Political /ced. by Seyla Benhabib. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4c©1996  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction The Democratic Moment and the Problem of Difference -- tPART ONE. DEMOCRATIC THEORY: FOUNDATIONS AND PERSPECTIVES -- tOne Three Normative Models of Democracy -- tTwo Fugitive Democracy -- tThree Using Power/Fighting Power: The Polity -- tFour Toward a Deliberative Model of Democratic Legitimacy -- tFive Procedure and Substance in Deliberative Democracy -- tSix Communication and the Other: Beyond Deliberative Democracy -- tPART TWO. EQUALITY, DIFFERENCE, AND PUBLIC REPRESENTATION -- tSeven Dealing with Difference: A Politics of Ideas, or a Politics of Presence? -- tEight Three Forms of Group-Differentiated Citizenship in Canada -- tNine Diversity and Democracy: Representing Differences -- tTen Democracy, Difference, and the Right of Privacy -- tEleven Gender Equity and the Welfare State: A Postindustrial Thought Experiment -- tPART THREE. CULTURE, IDENTITY, AND DEMOCRACY -- tTwelve Democracy, Power, and the "Political" -- tThirteen Difference, Dilemmas, and the Politics of Home -- tFourteen Democracy and Multiculturalism -- tFifteen The Performance of Citizenship: Democracy, Gender, and Difference in the French Revolution -- tSixteen Peripheral Peoples and Narrative Identities: Arendtian Reflections on Late Modernity -- tPART FOUR. DOES DEMOCRACY NEED FOUNDATIONS? -- tSeventeen Idealizations, Foundations, and Social Practices -- tEighteen Democratic Theory and Democratic Experience -- tNineteen Democracy, Philosophy, and Justification -- tTwenty Foundationalism and Democracy -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe global trend toward democratization of the last two decades has been accompanied by the resurgence of various politics of "identity/difference." From nationalist and ethnic revivals in the countries of east and central Europe to the former Soviet Union, to the politics of cultural separatism in Canada, and to social movement politics in liberal western-democracies, the negotiation of identity/difference has become a challenge to democracies everywhere. This volume brings together a group of distinguished thinkers who rearticulate and reconsider the foundations of democratic theory and practice in the light of the politics of identity/difference. In Part One Jürgen Habermas, Sheldon S. Wolin, Jane Mansbridge, Seyla Benhabib, Joshua Cohen, and Iris Marion Young write on democratic theory. Part Two--on equality, difference, and public representation--contains essays by Anne Phillips, Will Kymlicka, Carol C. Gould, Jean L. Cohen, and Nancy Fraser; and Part Three--on culture, identity, and democracy--by Chantal Mouffe, Bonnie Honig, Fred Dallmayr, Joan B. Landes, and Carlos A. Forment. In the last section Richard Rorty, Robert A. Dahl, Amy Gutmann, and Benjamin R. Barber write on whether democracy needs philosophical foundations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDemocracy. 0aEthnicity. 0aNationalism. 0aSocial movements. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh1 aBarber, Benjamin R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenhabi